  "texts": [
    "For example, the proteome of SARS-CoV-2 harbors ~10 4 potential 9-mer HLA-I antigens.",
    "Bioinformatic analyses typically seek for ~1% of these peptides as predicted presented antigens per HLA allele 77, corresponding to general estimates of the viral peptidome fraction that binds to HLAs 78.",
    "Figure 2 illustrates how the different ML concepts and methods in Box 1 and Box 3 have been adapted to the prediction of HLA-I antigen presentation (see also refs.",
    "18, 19 for comprehensive reviews).",
    "Existing ML predictors range from unsupervised clustering methods to perform binding motif deconvolution from unannotated eluted ligand data, like MixMHCp and MixMHCpred [79] [80] [81] (Fig. 2a), to feed-forward neural networks trained in a supervised way to predict peptide presentation from known peptide-HLA pairs, like MHCflurry 82, 83 and the NetMHC and NetMHCpan suites [84] [85] [86] [87] [88] (Fig."
  ]
}